# Kui and OpenWhisk 

Kui now includes visual enhancements for working with [Apache Openwhisk](https://openwhisk.apache.org/). 

## Creating and Viewing Resources

When creating an OpenWhisk resource, or viewing an existing resource, you will be able to investigate the multiple aspects of the resource.

### Using `let` for Quick Prototyping

To help with quick ad-hoc prototyping of OpenWhisk actions, you may use the `let` command. For example, the following command will create a simple action that echoes its input. Upon creating the action, you will be presented with that multi-aspect view.

props.children:
## Working with Activations

Kui also provides a suite of visualizations to help with understanding the activations of your OpenWhisk actions.

- The **grid view** provides a dense view over your activations. The cells of the grid are colored according to the duration of the activation.

- The **sequence diagram** view helps with understanding the temporal relationship between a large number of activations. It can also help with gauging the penalty of cold start overheads.

- The **trace view** provides a similar temporary summary for the component activations of a sequence activation.

### `dopar`: Utility command to invoke an action many times

To help with performance testing your actions, you may use the Kui `dopar` command.

## Working with Activations

Kui also provides a suite of visualizations to help with understanding the activations of your OpenWhisk actions.

- The **grid view** provides a dense view over your activations. The cells of the grid are colored according to the duration of the activation.

- The **sequence diagram** view helps with understanding the temporal relationship between a large number of activations. It can also help with gauging the penalty of cold start overheads.

- The **trace view** provides a similar temporary summary for the component activations of a sequence activation.

### The Grid View

Now let us view these activations in a grid. In Kui, you may use `$` interchangeably, as an abbreviation for `activation`.

props.children:
In the default Kui theme, the cells are colored along a teal-to-purple spectrum. The teal end represents the fastest activations, while the purple end represents the slowest.

### The Trace View

Let us click on one of the purple (slower) activations, to see if we can find out what is going on to make it perform poorly. Clicking on any grid cell will show a multi-aspect summary of the selected activation.
